\subsection*{Growth chamber study} 

For our growth chamber studies, we collected branch cuttings from our highest and lowest latitude populations in each transect, with sampling in our eastern study occurring from 20-28 January 2015 and sampling for our western study from 19-28 October 2019. In both studies, we included a total of eight distinct treatments consisting of two levels of chilling, forcing, and photoperiods (Fig. \ref{fig:concept}). We recorded budburst stages of each sample every 1-3 days for up to four months, defining the day of budburst as the day of budbreak or shoot elongation (denoted as code 07 by \citet[][]{Finn2007}). For a more detailed discussion of study sample collection and methods see \citet[][]{Flynn2018} for details on our eastern study and \citet[][]{LoughnanInPrep} for details on our western study. \\

\subsection*{Statistical Analysis}
Our analysis combined our \emph{in situ} trait data with budburst data from the controlled environment. For each trait, we developed a joint Bayesian model, in which the relationship between traits and cues is used to estimate budburst. This statistical approach improves upon previous analyses of multiple traits, as it allows us to carry through uncertainty between trait and phenology data---and better partitions the drivers of variation in species phenologies\\

Our joint model consists of two parts. The first is a hierarchical linear model, which partitions the variation of individual observations (\emph{i}) of a given trait value ($Y_{\text{trait}}$) to account for the effects of species (\emph{j}), population-level differences arising from transects, latitude, as well as the interaction between transects and latitude (\emph{transect} $\cdot$ \emph{latitude}), and finally, residual variation or `measurement error' ($\sigma_{\text{m}}^2$). \\

\begin{align}
  Y_{\text{trait}_{i,j}} \sim \emph{Normal}(\mu_{i,j}, \sigma_{\text{m}}^2)
\end{align}

\begin{align}
  \mu_{i,j} = \alpha_{\text{grand trait}} + \alpha_{\text{trait}_j} + \beta_\text{transect} \times transect + \\
  \beta_{\text{latitude}} \times latitude + \beta_{\text{transect} \cdot \text{latitude}} \times (transect \cdot latitude)\\
\end{align}
\begin{align}
  \boldsymbol{\alpha_{\text{trait}}} 
  \begin{bmatrix}
 \alpha_{\text{trait}_1}\\
 \alpha_{\text{trait}_2} \\ 
 \ldots \\
 \alpha_{\text{trait}_n}
 \end{bmatrix}
  % \boldsymbol{\alpha_{\text{trait}}} = \{\alpha_{\text{trait}_1}, ..., \alpha_{\text{trait}_n}\}^T 
  \text{ such that }  \boldsymbol{\alpha_{\text{trait}}} \sim \emph{Normal}(0, \sigma_{\text{trait}}^2) \\
\end{align}

We include transect as a dummy variable (0/1) and latitude as a continuous variable in our model. We modeled traits using natural units, with the exception of leaf mass area, which was rescaled by 100 for numeric stability in the model. Our model also includes partial pooling for species---which controls for variation in the number of trait estimates per species and trait variability---using these species-level estimates as predictors for each cue ($\beta_{\text{chilling,j}}$, $\beta_{\text{forcing,j}}$, $\beta_{\text{photoperiod,j}}$).\\

\begin{align} 
  \beta_{\text{chilling}_j}= \alpha_{\text{chilling},j} + \beta_{\text{trait.chilling}} \times \alpha_{\text{trait},j} \\
  \beta_{\text{forcing}_j}= \alpha_{\text{forcing},j} + \beta_{\text{trait.forcing}} \times \alpha_{\text{trait},j} \nonumber \\
  \beta_{\text{photoperiod}_j}= \alpha_{\text{photoperiod},j} + \beta_{\text{trait.photoperiod}} \times \alpha_{\text{trait},j} \nonumber
\end{align}

In addition to the species-level estimates, the second part of our model estimates the overall effect of each trait on each cue ($\beta_{\text{trait}.\text{chilling}}$, $\beta_{\text{trait}.\text{forcing}}$, $\beta_{\text{trait}.\text{photoperiod}}$). From this we can estimate how well traits explain species-level differences---by estimating the the species-level cue variation not explained by traits ($\alpha_{\text{chilling,j}}$, $\alpha_{\text{forcing,j}}$, $\alpha_{\text{photoperiod,j}}$) and individual species responses to cues ($chilling$, $forcing$, $photoperiod$, respectively). Finally, our model estimates the residual budburst variation across species ($Y_{\text{pheno,j}}$), observations ($\sigma_{\text{d}}^2$), as well as the variation in cues not attributed to the trait (using partial pooling).

\begin{align}
  Y_{\text{pheno}_{i,j}} \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu_{i,j}, \sigma_{\text{d}}^2)
\end{align}
with
\begin{align} 
  \mu_{i,j} = \alpha_{\text{pheno}_j} + \beta_{\text{chilling}_j} \cdot chilling  +  \beta_{\text{forcing}_j} \cdot forcing +  \beta_{\text{photoperiod}_j} \cdot photoperiod
\end{align}

\noindent where $\alpha_{\text{pheno}_j}$, $\alpha_{\text{chilling}_j}$, $\alpha_{\text{forcing}_j}$, and $\alpha_{\text{photoperiod}_j}$ are elements of the normal random vectors:

\begin{align}
  \boldsymbol{\alpha_{\text{pheno}}} = \{\alpha_{\text{pheno}_1}, ..., \alpha_{\text{pheno}_n}\}^T \text{ such that } \boldsymbol{\alpha_{\text{pheno}}} \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu_{\text{pheno}}, \sigma_{\text{pheno}}^2) \\
  \boldsymbol{\alpha_{\text{chilling}}} = \{\alpha_{\text{chilling}_1}, ..., \alpha_{\text{chilling}_n}\}^T \text{ such that } \boldsymbol{\alpha_{\text{chilling}}} \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu_{\text{chilling}}, \sigma_{\text{chilling}}^2) \nonumber \\
  \boldsymbol{\alpha_{\text{forcing}}} = \{\alpha_{\text{forcing}_1}, ..., \alpha_{\text{forcing}_n}\}^T \text{ such that } \boldsymbol{\alpha_{\text{forcing}}} \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu_{\text{forcing}}, \sigma_{\text{forcing}}^2) \nonumber \\
  \boldsymbol{\alpha_{\text{photo}}} = \{\alpha_{\text{photo}_1}, ..., \alpha_{\text{photo}_n}\}^T \text{ such that } \boldsymbol{\alpha_{\text{photo}}} \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu_{\text{photo}}, \sigma_{\text{photo}}^2) \nonumber
\end{align}

We modeled each trait individually, with the exception of ring-porosity, which we compared across species using the posterior estimates of our wood stem density model, allowing us to account for inherent differences in wood anatomy across species and growth form. We included all three cues (chilling, forcing, and photoperiod) as continuous variables in our model, as well as all two-way interactions between cues and between cues and sites. We converting chilling temperatures to total chill portions, including both the chilling experienced in the field prior to sampling and during the experiment. For this we used local weather station data and the chillR package \citep[v. 0.73.1,][]{Luedeling2020}. To account for differences in thermoperiodicity between the two studies \citep{Buonaiuto2023}, we also converted forcing temperatures to mean daily temperatures for each treatment. Finally, we $z$-scored each cue and site using two standard deviations to allow direct comparisons between results across parameters \citep{Gelman2008}. \\

For each model we used trait specific priors that were weakly informative. We validated our choice of priors using prior predictive checks and confirmed model stability under wider priors. All models were coded in the Stan programming language for Bayesian models using the rstan package \citep{rstan2018} in R version 4.3.1 \citep{R}. All models met basic diagnostic checks, including no divergences, high effective sample sizes (\emph{$n_{eff}$}) that exceeded 10\% of the number of iterations, and $\hat{R}$ values close to 1. We report our model estimates as the mean values with 90\% uncertainty intervals (UI), interpreting parameter estimates with intervals that overlap to be statistically similar to each other and those that include zero to have small effects. \\%Estimates are given to one decimal place, as this best represents the level of precision we can infer from our data \citep{GelmanROS}.\\

\section*{Results}

Across our eight populations, we measured \Sexpr{nSpp} species of which \Sexpr{nSppE} were in our eastern transect and \Sexpr{nSppW} in our western transect. These include species dominant in both the understory and canopy layer, with our eastern community consisting of \Sexpr{nSppES} shrubs and \Sexpr{nSppET} trees, our western community consisting of \Sexpr{nSppWS} shrubs and \Sexpr{nSppWT} trees, and three species that occurred in both transects. In total we measured traits of \Sexpr{noIndiv} unique individuals between the two transects across our five \emph{in situ} traits: height ($n$ = \Sexpr{nHt}), diameter ($n$ = \Sexpr{nDBH}), wood stem density ($n$ = \Sexpr{nSSD}), leaf mass area ($n$ = \Sexpr{nLMA}), leaf nitrogen content ($n$ = \Sexpr{nLNC}). Across our two growth chamber studies, we made observations of \Sexpr{noIndivPheno} samples, with our observations of budburst spanning 82 and \Sexpr{totalDays} days for our eastern and western studies respectfully. \\

Most of our traits showed some variation by latitude within each transect, with a strong interactive effect between transect and latitude (Fig. \ref{fig:tranInt}). Leaf nitrogen content was the only trait to vary with latitude alone, with low latitude communities on both our eastern and western transects having greater values of leaf nitrogen content than communities at higher latitudes (\Sexpr{lncLat}, UI: \Sexpr{lower_lncLat}, \Sexpr{upper_lncLat}, Table \ref{tabLNC}). The strongest negative interaction was observed for height (\Sexpr{htLatTran}, UI: \Sexpr{lower_htLatTran}, \Sexpr{upper_htLatTran}), while the strongest positive interaction was observed for leaf mass area (\Sexpr{lmaLatTran}, UI: \Sexpr{lower_lmaLatTran}, \Sexpr{upper_lmaLatTran}). Overall, woody species in our eastern community exhibited greater heights, diameter, and wood stem density but decreases in leaf mass area with increasing latitude. But in our western communities height and wood stem density decreased with latitude, while diameter and leaf mass area both increased (Fig. \ref{fig:tranInt}). In addition to the differences we found across populations, we also observed considerable differences between individual species, which varied considerably and up to \Sexpr{htFold} fold for some traits (Fig. \ref{fig:traitSlopes}). \\

% Paragraph on photo
We found that three of our four traits had a strong relationship with photoperiod, but not always in the direction we predicted. Taller species with larger trunk diameters and leaves with high nitrogen content had stronger responses with longer photoperiods (Fig. \ref{fig:traitSlopes} c, i, o; Tables \ref{tabHt}, \ref{tabDBH}, \ref{tabLNC}). But, contrary to our expectation, species with denser, high leaf mass area leaves had weaker photoperiod responses, allowing them to potentially budburst under shorter photoperiods (Fig. \ref{fig:traitSlopes}f).\\

% paragraph on chilling and forcing
Temperature cues ($\beta_{\text{trait.chilling}}$ and $\beta_{\text{trait.forcing}}$) exhibited no relationships with individual traits, but by accounting for the effects of leaf or wood traits, we found the importance of our three cues the vary by trait. Our models of height (\Sexpr{htMuCSpMean}, UI: \Sexpr{lower_htMuCSpMean}, \Sexpr{upper_htMuCSpMean}), diameter (\Sexpr{dbhMuCSpMean}, UI: \Sexpr{lower_dbhMuCSpMean}, \Sexpr{upper_dbhMuCSpMean}), wood stem density (\Sexpr{ssdMuCSpMean}, UI: \Sexpr{lower_ssdMuCSpMean}, \Sexpr{upper_ssdMuCSpMean}), and leaf nitrogen content (\Sexpr{lncMuCSpMean}, UI: \Sexpr{lower_lncMuCSpMean}, \Sexpr{upper_lncMuCSpMean}) all estimated chilling as the strongest cue of budburst ($\beta_{\text{chilling}}$), with more chilling advancing budburst. Our model of leaf mass area, however, estimated photoperiod as the strongest cue ($\beta_{\text{photoperiod}}$, \Sexpr{lmaMuPSpMean}, UI: \Sexpr{lower_lmaMuPSpMean}, \Sexpr{upper_lmaMuPSpMean}). After accounting for the effects of traits, only our height and diameter model found all three environmental cues to drive budburst timing (Tables \ref{tabHt}, \ref{tabDBH}). Our models of wood stem density and leaf nitrogen content in turn found temperature cues alone to shape budburst (Tables \ref{tabSSD}, \ref{tabLNC}), while our model of leaf mass area found a large response to only photoperiod (Table \ref{tabLMA}).\\

In synthesizing the effects of multiple traits across species, our results can be used to make generalizations across ecologically important groups of species. But only some of our models estimated clear gradients in species timing between trees and shrubs. In particular, we found height to have large correlations between budburst timing and trait values, with earlier estimates of budburst for shrubs (with a mean day of budburst of \Sexpr{meanShrubBB})---especially under greater cues---and later budburst estimates for trees (with a mean day of budburst of (\Sexpr{meanTreeBB}, Fig. \ref{fig:bbShrubTree}). Diameter at breast height showed similar trends as estimates from our height model (results not shown). But this was not the case for our two leaf traits. Leaf nitrogen content, for example, showed no distinct separation between shrub and tree functional groups (Fig. \ref{fig:bbShrubTree}).\\
